                    "rationale": "In TLS, rapid tumor cell destruction releases intracellular contents causing hyperkalemia (peaked T-waves, widened QRS), hyperphosphatemia (which binds calcium causing reciprocal hypocalcemia manifesting as tingling and cramping), hyperuricemia, and acute kidney injury (rising creatinine, oliguria). The uric acid decrease to 4.1 mg/dL is actually explained by the rasburicase administration (which enzymatically converts uric acid to allantoin), so while TLS would typically cause hyperuricemia, the pharmacologic intervention has contradicted that expected finding. Note: the lab specimen must not be placed on ice, as this can cause falsely low uric acid readings with rasburicase. The temperature of 37.4°C is within normal range and unrelated to TLS pathophysiology. The paresthesias and muscle cramping are direct manifestations of hypocalcemia secondary to calcium-phosphate precipitation, a hallmark of TLS.",
